			article
				h1 Evolution of The Web

		section#Begining60s.begining.y60.header
			h2 1969

		section.y60
			article
				p Charles Goldfarb, Edward Mosher and Raymond Lorie developed "GML"
				p [ whose surname initials were used to make up the term GML ].

		section#Begining80s.begining.y80.header
			h2 1980

		section.y80
			#e01.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.5")
			article
				h3 Guido van Rossum conceived Python.

		section.y80.header
			h2 1985

		section.y80
			#e02.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="2")
			article
				h3 October 4:
				p The Free Software Foundation is founded by
				p Richard Matthew Stallman.

		section.y80.header
			h2 1986

		section.y80
			article
				h3 October:
				p SGML (The Standard Generalized Markup Language)
				p was accepted followed by a minor Technical Corrigendum.

		section.y80.header
			h2 1987

		section.y80
			#e04.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.4")
			article
				p Larry Wall developed "Perl".
				p there are various backronyms in use, the most well-known being
				p "Practical Extraction and Reporting Language".

		section.y80.header
			h2 1989

		section.y80
			article
				p Tim Berners-Lee wrote a memo
				p proposing an Internet-based hypertext system.

		section.y80
			#e03.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 December:
				p Python implementation start.

		section#Begining90s.begining.y90.header
			h2 1990

		section.y90
			article
				p Tim Berners-Lee specified HTML (HyperText Markup Language)
				p and wrote the server software
				p [ Berners-Lee considered HTML to be an application of SGML ].

		section.y90
			#e05.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.6")
			article
				p Ruby its developed by Yukihiro "Matz" Matsumoto.
				p two names were proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby",
				p Matsumoto later noted that "Ruby"
				p was the birthstone of one of his colleagues.

		section.y90
			article
				h3 December 25:
				p Berners-Lee made the first web browser "WorldWideWeb".
				p [ later renamed to Nexus to avoid confusion ].

		section.y90.header
			h2 1992

		section.y90
			article
				h3 April 15:
				p Born "Erwise" the first web browser with a graphical user interface.
				p [ project initiated by Robert Cailliau ]

		section.y90.header
			h2 1993

		section.y90
			article
				h3 January 23:
				p Born "Mosaic" the web browser credited by popularizing
				p the World Wide Web.

		section.y90
			#e14.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.6")
			article
				h3 June 8:
				p Born The first Microsoft Windows browser under the name of "Cello".

		section.y90.header
			h2 1994

		section.y90
			#e06.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				p Rasmus Lerdorf created "PHP".
				p originally stood for Personal Home Page, it now stands for
				p PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor
				p [ which is a recursive backronym ].

		section.y90
			article
				h3 October:
				p It's founded by Tim Berners-Lee the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C),
				p the main international standards organization
				p for the World Wide Web.

		section.y90
			article
				h3 October 10:
				p CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)
				p was proposed by H&Aring;kon Wium Lie.

		section.y90
			#e15.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 December 15:
				p Netscape Navigator (based on Mosaic Web Browser)
				p made his firsts steps.

		section.y90.header
			h2 1995

		section.y90
			#e11.significante.back
			article
				h3 The Begining of "Opera" (Web Browser).

		section.y90
			article
				h3 HTML 2.0 Happens!
				p The first HTML specification intended to be treated as
				p a standard against which future implementations should be based.

		section.y90
			article
				p It's developed "Mocha" by Brendan Eich while working on Netscape.
				p although it was officially called LiveScript.
				p later on september it's renamed to Javascript
				p [ even though it wasn't related to Java ].

		section.y90
			#e11.significante.back
			article
				h3 March 1:
				p Born "Yahoo! Search".
				p The word "Yahoo" is an acronym for "Yet Another Hierarchical Officious Oracle".

		section.y90
			#e07.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.6")
			article
				h3 August 16:
				p Internet Explorer was released.

		section.y90
			#e11.significante.back
			article
				h3 December 15:
				p It's Founded AltaVista (the web search engine).
				p [ whom later in July 8 of 2003 was purchased by Yahoo! ].

		section.y90.header
			h2 1996

		section.y90
			article
				h3 CSS 1 was released
				p Bert Bos' proposal was influential also he became co-author of CSS 1
				p and is regarded as co-creator of CSS.

		section.y90
			article
				h3 January:
				p As a research project by Larry Page and Sergey Brin born "Google".

		section.y90
			article
				h3 August-November:
				p The first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
				p XML (Extensible Markup Language) an application profile of SGML.

		section.y90
			#e17.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.6")
			article
				h3 October 14:
				p KDE created "Konqueror" under the KHTML layout engine.

		section.y90.header
			h2 1997

		section.y90
			article
				h3 December:
				p HTML 4.0 was published as a W3C Recommendation
				p with three variations:
				p -- Strict, Transitional and Frameset --

		section.y90.header
			h2 1998

		section.y90
			article
				p PGML (Precision Graphics Markup Language)
				p it's submitted to the W3C.
				p [ that was not adopted as a recommendation].

		section.y90
			article
				h3 February 10:
				p XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation.

		section.y90
			article
				h3 April:
				p MathML 1 (Mathematical Markup Language)
				p was released as a W3C recommendation as the first
				p XML language to be recommended by the W3C.

		section.y90.header
			h2 1999

		section.y90
			article
				h3 HTML 4.01 was published!

		section.y90
			article
				p After PGML wasnt adopted as a recomendation
				p start the development of SVG (Scalable Vector Graphic).

		section.y90
			article
				h3 June:
				p The earliest CSS 3 drafts were published.

		section#Begining2000s.begining.y2k.header
			h2 2000

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 January 26:
				p XHTML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation.

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 July:
				p C# was publicly announced!! they use the number sign because the sharp symbol
				p is not available on the standard keyboard. "sharp" resembles a ligature of
				p four "+" symbols implying that the language is an increment of C++.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2001

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 SVG 1.0 became a W3C Recomendation.

		section.y2k
			#e16.significante.front(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 January 15:
				p Jimmy Wales and Larry Sanger launched Wikipedia.

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 February:
				p Appeared MathML 2.0.

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 May 31:
				p XHTML 1.1 became a W3C Recommendation.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2002

		section.y2k
			#e08.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 September 23:
				p Under the name of Phoneix born Firefox.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2003

		section.y2k
			#e09.significante.back
			article
				h3 January 7:
				p Safari is released as a public beta.
				p It was based on Apple's internal fork of the KHTML rendering engine
				p [ WebKit ].

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 October:
				p MathML 2.0 was published as the final release
				p by the W3C math working group.

		section.y2k
			#e10.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 May 27:
				p Born Wordpress by Matt Mullenweg and Mike Little.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2004

		section.y2k
			article
				p John Gruber with Aaron Swartz created the "Markdown language".

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 Development of HTML5 began.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2005

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 June:
				p WebKit was released as open source.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2006

		section.y2k
			article
				p Hampton Catlin created "Haml" (HTML Abstraction Markup Language).

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 August 26:
				p Influenced by cssQuery Was Released Jquery 1.0
				p by John Resig at BarCamp.

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2007

		section.y2k
			article
				p Hampton Catlin created "Sass" (Syntactically Awesome Stylesheets).

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2008

		section.y2k
			#e13.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.8")
			article
				h3 October 28:
				p HTML5 is completed and standardized.

		section.y2k
			#e12.significante.back(data-stellar-ratio="0.7")
			article
				h3 September 2:
				p Google Chrome was released as a beta version.
				p [ Under the WebKit layout engine that was already open source ]

		section.y2k.header
			h2 2009

		section.y2k
			article
				h3 Born "Less"!
				p a CSS builder system by the hand of Alexis Sellier and influenced by "Sass".

		section.y2k
			article
				p A ninth draft of XHTML 2.0 was expected to appear,
				p but on July 2, the W3C decided to let
				p the XHTML2 Working Group charter expire by that year's end.

		section.y2k
			article
				p Born AngularJS by Mi&scaron;ko Hevery and Adam Abrons
				p at Brat Tech LLC.

		section#Begining2010s.begining.y2k1.header
			h2 2010

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 October:
				p MathML 3 specification was released as a
				p W3C Recommendation.

		section.y2k1.header
			h2 2011

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 June 7:
				p CSS 2.1 was published as a W3C Recommendation.

		section.y2k1.header
			h2 2013

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 February 12:
				p Opera announced it would drop
				p its own Presto engine in favour of WebKit.

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 April 3:
				p Google announced that it would form
				p a new rendering engine known as Blink.
				p the same day, Opera confirmed that it would follow Google.

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 April 18:
				p Jquery Dropped support for IE[6-8] for performance
				p improvements and reduction in filesize,
				p releasing the version 2.03.

		section.y2k1.header
			h2 2014

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 October:
				p HTML 5 was published as a W3C Recommendation.

		section.y2k1.header
			h2 NOW

		section.y2k1
			article
				h3 W3C is still working on the standard of XHTML5.

